    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants are suffering from a condition known as \"lower stem chlorosis.\" This is often caused by a lack of iron in the soil, which is essential for the plants to produce chlorophyll. You might want to consider adding some iron chelates to your soil, which are like little iron nuggets that the plants can gobble up easily. Also, make sure your soil pH is in the right range, as iron can be less available to plants in either too acidic or too alkaline soil. Just remember, if your soil is too acidic, you might need to add some lime to balance it out, and if it's too alkaline, you might need to add some sulfur. Keep an eye on your plants, and they'll thank you for the extra iron and balanced soil pH. Happy gardening, and may your tomatoes grow as strong as a well-fed goblin!",
      "source": "target",
